etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in James VI & I (1566–1625), king of Scotland, England, and Ireland. From sprout + -er

definitions: A person who or thing which causes or encourages plants, etc., to sprout.
Chiefly with of. A person who grows, produces, or develops something specified.
A thing that sprouts up or forth, now especially with reference to hair.

notes.text: Earliest in †sprouter out: a new shoot or sprout.

definitions: Frequently with modifying word, as early, late, quick, etc. A plant, tree, seed, etc., which produces shoots or new growth, especially quickly or profusely.
A child or young person who grows or develops, especially quickly.
(chiefly North American). Originally: a person who removes sprouts from a potato tuber. Later more usually: a tool or machine which performs this function. Compare "sprout".
A container in which seeds (especially of mung beans) are placed to sprout.
